Serialized EMF model instances rely heavily on the ability to support cross document references in pretty much the same style as appears in standard .hmtl documents, i.e., relative references to anchors in other documents. Right now our ability to browse models in a CVS respository is extremely limited because starting with an IStorageEditorInput we have effectively no good way to turn that into a URI so the best we can do is something like this (from EcoreEditor):

  /**
   * This is the method called to load a resource into the editing domain's resource set based on the editor's input.
   * <!-- begin-user-doc -->
   * <!-- end-user-doc -->
   * @generated
   */
  public void createModelGen()
  {
    // Assumes that the input is a file object.
    //
    IFileEditorInput modelFile = (IFileEditorInput)getEditorInput();
    URI resourceURI = URI.createPlatformResourceURI(modelFile.getFile().getFullPath().toString(), true);;
    Exception exception = null;
    Resource resource = null;
    try
    {
      // Load the resource through the editing domain.
      //
      resource = editingDomain.getResourceSet().getResource(resourceURI, true);
    }
    catch (Exception e)
    {
      exception = e;
      resource = editingDomain.getResourceSet().getResource(resourceURI, false);
    }

    Diagnostic diagnostic = analyzeResourceProblems(resource, exception);
    if (diagnostic.getSeverity() != Diagnostic.OK)
    {
      resourceToDiagnosticMap.put(resource,  analyzeResourceProblems(resource, exception));
    }
    editingDomain.getResourceSet().eAdapters().add(problemIndicationAdapter);
  }

  public void createModel()
  {
    if (getEditorInput() instanceof IFileEditorInput)
    {
      editingDomain.getResourceSet().getURIConverter().getURIMap().putAll(EcorePlugin.computePlatformURIMap());
      createModelGen();
    }
    else
    {
      Exception exception = null;
      Resource resource = null;
      IStorageEditorInput storageEditorInput = (IStorageEditorInput)getEditorInput();
      try
      {
        IStorage storage = storageEditorInput.getStorage();
        resource = editingDomain.createResource("*.ecore");
        resource.setURI(URI.createURI(storage.getFullPath().toString()));
        resource.load(storage.getContents(), null);
      }
      catch (Exception e)
      {
        exception = e;
      }

      Diagnostic diagnostic = analyzeResourceProblems(resource, exception);
      if (diagnostic.getSeverity() != Diagnostic.OK)
      {
        resourceToDiagnosticMap.put(resource,  analyzeResourceProblems(resource, exception));
      }
      editingDomain.getResourceSet().eAdapters().add(problemIndicationAdapter);      
    }
  }

You can see that if we have an IFileEditorInput, we can create a "platform resource" URI of the form platform:/resource/<project-name>/<path-to-file> and load the resource for that URI; the URI converter is smart enough to recognize this scheme and will access the underlying IFile to read and write the contents.   The scheme is also registered as real URL so technically we could just use a URL, but that would bypass the IFile APIs (I think).  Relative references work nicely, because they are resolved against this absolute URI.

But for IStorageEditorInput we are a bit hosed.  The best we can do is get the input stream from that editor input object and load directly from that input stream.  Because there is no absolute URI, we can't resolve relative URIs within the stream.  And even if there was an absolute URI, we'd need the ability to convert that URI to something we can use to access the stream in much the same way as we can convert a platform:/resource URI to an IFile.

I believe there is talk to define a URI in this type of form:

  cvs://:pserver:anonymous@dev.eclipse.org:/cvsroot/tools#path/to/project,tag

This will help a lot!  If such a thing would correspond to a real live URL handler, i.e., if you could create a URL for the above to get a stream, that would be good.  But an alternative would be for some type of mechanism that would allow EMF's URIConverter to be implemented in some other way. All that's really needed in the URIConverter is some way (any way) to take the URI and fetch its input stream.

The above URI form is not ideal though because a typical usage pattern is to use the URI for accessing the resource and append a fragment for accessing the contents within that resource.  So the URI for accessing the resource should avoid using the fragment.  This alternative would be effectively the same functionally but much better syntactically:

  cvs://:pserver:anonymous@dev.eclipse.org:/cvsroot/tools?path/to/project,tag

I.e., specify the path into the repository as the query string rather than the fragment so that a reference like this will work

cvs://:pserver:anonymous@dev.eclipse.org:/cvsroot/tools?path/to/project,tag#<fragment>

It would be wonderful if this type of thing could be supported for all team repositories so that browsing of EMF models (or just .html files for that matter) could be fully supported.

