Here's a stripped-down example that shows the difference:

public class Try {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		new Try().new Inner();
	}

	int fField= -1;
	class Inner extends Super {
		public void access() {
			System.out.println(fField);
		}
	}
}

class Super {
	public Super() {
		access();
	}
	public void access() {
		System.out.println("Super#access()");;
	}
}

Right ... it doesn't really do anything in 3.2.  The service itself is internal (and the schema was left in place).

The IWorkbench.getAdapter(*) is a shorthand that shouldn't be used.  It should have read:
IWorkbench wb = ...;
wb.getAdapter(ICommandImageService.class);

Except in 3.2 all services go through the service locator API:
IWorkbench wb = ...;
wb.getService(ICommandImageService.class);

The state of this particular extension is still in flux with the new menu work in bug 154130.  It can't programmatically be used (it has no programmatic API) but if it was published and is used we'll still have to support it.

